<blockquote>
<p>I think they call her Ae because she simply can't comprehend being called a number. Surely, they would refer to it as SCP-811 in a professional setting, but when speaking with SCP-811, it would be best to refer to her as AE.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>^This is exactly it. Communication with 811 is difficult enough as it is, so calling her "Aé" when speaking to her streamlines out a lot of time and confusion as she tries to get you to understand that no, her name's Aé, <em>ah</em>-<em>eh</em>, how did you get "atey-leven" out of that? She doesn't know what "leven" is, but she knows what "ate" means. Are you making fun of her because of the way she eats? The fact that it's actually the numbers "eight eleven" go right over her head, because that doesn't make sense at all to her. Numbers are for counting, not for names, so why would they be calling her a number?</p>
<p>She's intelligent, sure, but she lacks the frame of reference that we pretty much take for granted because she grew up alone in a swamp, and she can't speak well for the same reason. Circumstances-wise, she's essentially the equivalent of a now-adult feral child who was abandoned at a young age (somewhere in the range of 4-7 years old), but not at birth.</p>
<p>Of course, when talking <em>about</em> her and not <em>to</em> her, she's SCP-811 all the time.</p>

